-- Japanese Stock Futures Climb on Profits, While Australian Index Fluctuates
-- B y   A k i k o   I k e d a   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 2010-10-24T23:32:42Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-24/japan-s-stock-futures-climb-on-profit-outlook-australian-index-fluctuates.html
Japanese  stock   futures  rose on
speculation corporate earnings will climb, while Australian
shares fluctuated.  American depositary receipts of Hitachi Ltd., a Japanese
maker of washing machines and power stations, and Komatsu Ltd.,
the world’s No. 2 maker of construction equipment, gained at
least 0.3 percent from the closing share price in Tokyo after
the Nikkei newspaper said their profits may exceed forecasts.
Virgin Blue Holdings Ltd., Australia’s second-biggest airline,
fell 1.1 percent in Sydney today after Macquarie Group Ltd. cut
its rating on the stock to “neutral” from “outperform.”
Santos Ltd., an Australian oil producer, climbed 1.5 percent in
Sydney after crude prices advanced.  “Commodity-related stocks will likely rise on higher oil
prices, and reports on strong earnings should also support the
market,” said  Toshiyuki Kanayama , a market analyst at Tokyo-
based Monex Inc.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 Stock Average  expiring in
December closed at 9,445 in Chicago on Oct. 22, compared with
9,425 in Singapore. They were bid in the pre-market at 9,420 in
Osaka, Japan, at 8:05 a.m. local time. Australia’s  S&P/ASX 200
Index  was little changed today, while New Zealand’s  NZX 50 Index 
rose 0.8 percent in Wellington.  Futures on the  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  were little
changed today. The index gained 0.2 percent in New York on Oct.
22 as earnings improved at companies from Schlumberger Ltd. to T.
Rowe Price Group Inc. Of the 132 companies in the S&P 500 that
reported results since Oct. 7, more than 85 percent have topped
analysts’ per-share earnings estimates, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.  G-20 Meeting  The Group of 20 agreed to “move towards more market
determined exchange rates systems that reflect underlying
economic fundamentals and refrain from competitive devaluation
of currencies,” its finance ministers and central bankers said
after talks on Oct. 23 in Gyeongju, South Korea.  The  MSCI Asia Pacific Index  has increased 7.9 percent in
2010, compared with gains of 6.1 percent by the  S&P 500  and 5.1
percent by the  Stoxx Europe 600 Index . Stocks in the Asian
benchmark are valued at 14.3 times estimated  earnings , compared
with 14 times for the S&P 500 and 12.3 times for the Stoxx 600.  The London Metal Exchange Index of prices for six
industrial metals including copper and aluminum gained 0.4
percent on Oct. 22. Crude oil for December delivery increased
1.4 percent $81.69 a barrel in New York.  Hitachi may report six-month operating profit of more than
200 billion yen ($2.46 billion), topping a previous forecast of
170 billion yen, the Nikkei newspaper reported, without citing
anyone.  The newspaper also said  Komatsu , the world’s second-largest
maker of construction machinery, may report operating profit of
200 billion yen for the year ending March 2011, exceeding a
forecast of 179 billion yen.  Oct. 29 is the peak for earnings reports in Japan, with 271
of the 1,662 companies in the Topix index scheduled to report
results, according to data compiled by Bloomberg.  To contact the reporters for this story:
